"Lighthill J.","Ocean spray and the thermodynamics of tropical cyclones",1999,"Journal of Engineering Mathematics","35","1-2",,"11","42",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032812479&partnerID=40&md5=fd4c3afe1991a2077429bdb033577ad9","Department of Mathematics, University College London, Gower Street, London WC1E 6BT, United Kingdom","Lighthill, J., Department of Mathematics, University College London, Gower Street, London WC1E 6BT, United Kingdom","Serious gaps in knowledge about ocean spray at wind speeds over 40m/s remain difficult to fill by observation or experiment; yet refined study of the thermodynamics of Tropical Cyclones (including typhoons and hurricanes) requires assessment of the hypothesis that 'spray cooling' at extreme wind speeds may act to reduce (i) the initial temperature of saturated air rising in the eyewall and so also (ii) the input of mechanical energy into the airflow as a whole. Such progressive reductions at higher speeds could, for example, make any possible influence of future global warming on Tropical Cyclone intensification largely self-limiting. In order to help in extrapolation of knowledge on ocean spray to extreme wind speeds, a probabilistic analysis is introduced which allows for the effects of gusts, gravity and evaporation on droplet distributions, yet in other respects is as simple as possible. Preliminary indications from this simplified analysis appear to confirm the potential importance of spray cooling.Serious gaps in knowledge about ocean spray at wind speeds over 40m/s remain difficult to fill by observation or experiment; yet refined study of the thermodynamics of Tropical Cyclones (including typhoons and hurricanes) requires assessment of the hypothesis that 'spray cooling' at extreme wind speeds may act to reduce (i) the initial temperature of saturated air rising in the eyewall and so also (ii) the input of mechanical energy into the airflow as a whole. Such progressive reductions at higher speeds could, for example, make any possible influence of future global warming on Tropical Cyclone intensification largely self-limiting. In order to help in extrapolation of knowledge on ocean spray to extreme wind speeds, a probabilistic analysis is introduced which allows for the effects of gusts, gravity and evaporation on droplet distributions, yet in other respects is as simple as possible. Preliminary indications from this simplified analysis appear to confirm the potential importance of spray cooling.","Droplets; Evaporation; Hurricanes; Spray; Typhoons","Drop formation; Evaporation; Extrapolation; Gravitation; Probability; Surface waters; Thermodynamics; Vapors; Wind; Wind effects; Droplets; Ocean spray; Probabilistic analysis; Spray cooling; Tropical cyclones; Wind speeds; Storms; fluid mechanics; ocean; wave",,,,,,"Andreas, E.L., Edson, J.B., Monahan, E.C., Rouault, M.P., Smith, S.D., The spray contribution to net evaporation from the sea: A review of recent progress (1995) Boundary Layer Meteorol., 72, pp. 3-52; De Cosmo, J., Katsaros, K.B., Smith, S.D., Anderson, R.J., Oost, W., Bumke, K., Chadwick, H., Air-sea exchange of water vapor and sensible heat: The HEXOS results (1996) J. Geophys. Res., 101, pp. 12001-12016; Pudov, V.D., The ocean response to the cyclones' influence and its possible role in their tracks (1993) Tropical Cyclone Disasters, pp. 367-376. , J. Lighthill, Zheng Zhemin, G. Holland and K. Emanuel (eds.) Beijing: Peking University Press; Fairall, C.W., Kepert, J.D., Holland, G.J., The effect of sea spray on surface energy transports over the ocean (1994) The Global Atmosphere and Ocean System, 2, pp. 121-142; Lighthill, J., Fluid Mechanics of Tropical Cyclones (1998) J. Theor. Comput. Fluid Dyn., 10, pp. 3-21; Emanuel, K.A., The theory of hurricanes (1991) Ann. Rev. Fluid Mech., 23, pp. 179-196; Lighthill, J., Holland, G.J., Gray, W.M., Landsea, C., Emanuel, K., Craig, G., Evans, J., Guard, C.P., Global climate change and tropical cyclones (1994) Bull. Amer. Met. Soc., 75, pp. 2147-2157; Henderson-Sellers, A., Zhang, H., Berz, G., Emanuel, K., Gray, W., Landsea, C., Holland, G., McGuffie, K., Tropical cyclones and global climate change: A post-IPCC assessment (1998) Bull. Amer. Met. Soc., 79, pp. 19-38; Petrichenko, S.A., Pudov, V.D., O parametrizatsii teplo- i vlago-obmena mezhdu okeanom i atmosferoi v tropikakh v shtormovykh usloviyakh (1996) Meteorologiya i Gidrologiya, (6), pp. 92-100; Black, P.G., Holland, G.J., Pudov, V., Observations of sea-air temperature difference in tropical cyclones as a function of wind speed: Importance of spray evaporation (1994) Parametrisation of Physical Processes: Papers Presented at the Fifth BMRC Modelling Workshop, November 1993, p. 87. , J.D. Jasper and P.J. Meighen (eds.) BMRC Research Report No. 46, Melbourne: Bureau of Meteorology Research Centre; Rouault, M.P., Mestayer, P.G., Schiestel, R., A model of evaporating spray droplet dispersion (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, pp. 7181-7200; Edson, J.B., Fairall, C.W., Spray droplet modeling. I. Lagrangian model simulation of the turbulent transport of evaporating droplets (1994) J. Geophys. Res., 99, pp. 25295-25311; De Leeuw, G., Profiling of aerosol concentrations, particle size distributions and relative humidity over the North Sea (1990) Tellus, 42 B, pp. 342-354; Taylor, G.I., Diffusion by continuous movements (1921) Proc. Lond. Math. Soc. (2), 20, pp. 196-212; Hunt, J.C.R., Turbulent diffusion from sources in complex flows (1985) Ann. Rev. Fluid Mech., 17, pp. 447-485; Pruppacher, H.R., Klett, J.D., (1997) Microphysics of Clouds and Precipitation, 2nd Edition, 954p. , Dordrecht: Kluwer","Lighthill, J.; Department of Mathematics, University College London, Gower Street, London WC1E 6BT, United Kingdom",,,"Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht, Netherlands",,,,,00220833,,JLEMA,,"English","J. Eng. Math.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-0032812479
